 frame with precedent and sworn affidavits, but we cannot command the breeze without lying to ourselves and breaking the covenant that gives our verdicts meaning. If we prove the Aerarium purchased famine to sell light, if we show they speculated on hunger through a hidden credit line, then the bell must not stutter on its way to a corner that favors their purse. I need your feet in the under-stairs and your ear for honest air, because the Orchids have already sold the chime pattern that would bend the tone into a ruse. Take this packet, keep it sealed, and walk as if the Old Song itself were balancing on your shoulders, because the smallest false note tonight could become a winter for half the city.\"},\n    {\"speaker\": \"Lyris Kael\", \"lines\": \"The Court taught me once that a bell rings truer in a headwind, and I learned to run toward the gust instead of away. My pendant is tuned to coax a whisper to the edge of hearing, but I will use it to keep the note clean, not to strangle it for anyone’s ledger. I will take your packet and I will keep it sealed until the clerk’s hand weighs it, because a truth unopened is still intact and a truth delivered late is a death knell just the same. If the Orchids trail me in the galleries, they will find only my shadow’s second choice of steps, because I will change my rhythm when the Old Song shifts. And if the Chainwardens bristle, I will bow to the oath on their sleeves, then slip past on a breath between ratchets, because I was born to measure a city by the space between clicks.\"},\n    {\"speaker\": \"Matron Vessa Greye\", \"lines\": \"You play at airflow and oaths as if both were games braided in colored ribbon, Lyris, but my ribbons cut deeper than silk and they bind longer than festivals. Remember our binding, Kael, the night I trimmed your debt-cord and taught you which gusts to ride and which to ignore, because memory is a kind of leash you wear gladly. I keep secrets alive by ensuring some truths are miscarried, a